[[File:Tsurugitachi-iwatokowakenomikoto-jinja torii.JPG|thumb|200px|right|Torii]]
'''Tsurugitachi Iwatokowake-no-Mikoto Shrine''' (つるぎたちいわとこわけのみことじんじゃ<ref>Name and reading from [http://shizuoka-jinjacho.or.jp/shokai/jinja.php?id=4402023 Tsurugitachi Iwatokowake-no-Mikoto Shrine] (Shizuoka Prefectural Association of Shinto Shrines).</ref>, also written '''Ken-tō Iwatoko-wake-no-Mikoto Shrine''') is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Yata, {{ill|lt=Mishima|Q653478|WD=Q653478|1=Mishima, Shizuoka}}, {{ill|lt=Shizuoka Prefecture|Q131320|WD=Q131320|1=Shizuoka Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}}, and under the former {{ill|lt=modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|lt=shrine ranking system|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} its rank was {{ill|lt=Village Shrine|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
The two enshrined deities are as follows{{Sfn|Mishima City History Vol. 2|1988|p=561}}.
* Tsurugitachi Iwatokowake-no-Mikoto (つるぎたちいわとこわけのみこと)
* {{ill|lt=Yamato Takeru|Q461258|WD=Q461258|lt=Yamato Takeru-no-Mikoto|1=Yamato Takeru}} (やまとたけるのみこと)
*: The origin of enshrining Yamato Takeru is unknown; it is presumed to derive from eastern expedition legends of Yamato Takeru{{Sfn|Shikinaisha Survey Report|1981}}.

=== History ===
=== Foundation ===
Shrine tradition says that worship of waterfalls called "First Falls," "Second Falls," and "Third Falls" was the origin of this shrine{{Sfn|Mishima City History Vol. 2|1988|p=561}}. The second and third falls were lost when the railway was laid, but the first falls remain in Takekura, Mishima (old name: Takekura){{Sfn|Mishima City History Vol. 2|1988|p=561}}. Another tradition says worship began from water springing from the "sword-like stone bed" at that Takekura site{{Sfn|Shikinaisha Survey Report|1981}}.

The plateau behind the shrine, now divided by a road, was formerly continuous with the shrine grounds, and ancient tomb groups have been confirmed on that plateau{{Sfn|Mishima City History Vol. 2|1988|p=561}}. From this, it is inferred that ritual worship was conducted here since the Kofun period{{Sfn|Shikinaisha Survey Report|1981}}.

=== Overview ===
In the {{ill|lt=Engi|Q1327274|WD=Q1327274|lt=Engi|1=Enchō}} 5 ({{ill|lt=927|Q30470|WD=Q30470|1=927}}) {{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}} {{ill|lt=Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}, the shikinaisha "Ken-tō Iwatoko-wake-no-Mikoto Shrine" in {{ill|lt=Tagata District|Q1154841|WD=Q1154841|1=Tagata District, Shizuoka}}, {{ill|lt=Izu Province|Q860928|WD=Q860928|1=Izu Province}}, is identified with this shrine{{Sfn|Place Names of Shizuoka Prefecture|2000}}. However, documentary evidence showing this identification descends only to a munafuda from {{ill|lt=Bunki|Q1324885|WD=Q1324885|1=Bunki}} 2 ({{ill|lt=1502|Q6137|WD=Q6137|1=1502}}){{Sfn|Shikinaisha Survey Report|1981}}. If this shrine is that shikinaisha, the stone beds and cliffs of the first, second, and third falls are said to represent the "sword/blade stone bed"{{Sfn|Shikinaisha Survey Report|1981}}. The reading is annotated "Tsurugitachi Iwatoko" in the Kujō family manuscript, while other manuscripts give "Kemutono Iwatoko"{{Sfn|Shikinaisha Survey Report|1981}}.

In medieval {{ill|lt=Izu no Kuni Shinkai-chō|Q17193087|WD=Q17193087|1=Izu no Kuni Shinkai-chō}}, the entry "Junior Fourth Rank Upper, Takiyama no Myōjin"{{Sfn|Place Names of Shizuoka Prefecture|2000}} or "Junior Fourth Rank Upper, Natsume no Myōjin"{{Sfn|Shikinaisha Survey Report|1981}}{{Sfn|Mishima City History Vol. 2|1988|p=561}} is identified with this shrine.

By the late medieval period it had syncretized with mountain ascetic worship, {{ill|lt=Shugendō|Q1483875|WD=Q1483875|1=Shugendō}}, and was also called "Ontake Daigongen"{{Sfn|Shikinaisha Survey Report|1981}}. Other detailed history is unclear, but the shrine preserves munafuda from {{ill|lt=Bunki|Q1324885|WD=Q1324885|1=Bunki}}, {{ill|lt=Tenshō|Q1145058|WD=Q1145058|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)}}, {{ill|lt=Genbun|Q1145754|WD=Q1145754|1=Genbun}}, {{ill|lt=Bunsei|Q1327119|WD=Q1327119|1=Bunsei}}, {{ill|lt=Kaei|Q1146125|WD=Q1146125|1=Kaei}}, etc., and displays a torii plaque from {{ill|lt=Meiwa|Q1146161|WD=Q1146161|1=Meiwa}}{{Sfn|Mishima City History Vol. 2|1988|p=561}}.

In {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 6 ({{ill|lt=1873|Q7757|WD=Q7757|1=1873}}), it was ranked as a {{ill|lt=Village Shrine|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}} in the modern shrine ranking system{{Sfn|Shikinaisha Survey Report|1981}}. During the Meiji separation of Shinto and Buddhism, this shrine was called "Ontake Shrine," but in {{ill|lt=Shōwa|Q327567|WD=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}} 23 ({{ill|lt=1948|Q5165|WD=Q5165|1=1948}}) it was renamed to the present "Tsurugitachi Iwatokowake-no-Mikoto Shrine"{{Sfn|Shikinaisha Survey Report|1981}}. It is also colloquially called "Yata Gomonsha"{{Sfn|Shikinaisha Survey Report|1981}}.

=== Divine rank ===
* Junior Fourth Rank Upper (''{{ill|lt=Izu no Kuni Shinkai-chō|Q17193087|WD=Q17193087|1=Izu no Kuni Shinkai-chō}}'') - "Takiyama no Myōjin"{{Sfn|Place Names of Shizuoka Prefecture|2000}} or "Natsume no Myōjin"{{Sfn|Mishima City History Vol. 2|1988|p=561}}.

